<h1>From Archibald Cary</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Chesterfd June 28. 1757</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>By Capt. Bell I receivd yours and am Greatly obligd to you, for your Good Intentions to Serve him, and must beleive that the hopes the Gover. his Given him is due to you.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Notwithstanding I hold no Milatary Commn I thought it my Duty to do all I Could to raise the Men due from our County for the presant Service and I judgd those most proper who would Volantaryly Inlist, I Applyd to the Bearer Drury Pucket a person who was last Year in the Service (&amp; as I have been Informd behavd well,) he is a Person of Good report here and has been Extriemly Active on this Occasion, he has desird me to Mention so much to you, and if he Should Continue to behave Well &amp; should deserve to be Taken Notice of a Serjts Post is the Most of his Ambition at presant; I hope you will Excuse this fredom.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>We are here a little unesey on a report of an Army of French Marching Your Way if it Should be so, I hope it will Give you an oppartunity of Gaining Fresh Lawrels And I do Assure you no Man more Wishes to See You Crownd with them than Your Most Obedt Humble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Archd Cary</p>
</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-04-02-pb-0272">[272]</span>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. Mrs Cary &amp; Miss Randolph joyn in wishing you that Sort of Glory which will most Indear you to the Fair Sex.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>

</div>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">A.C.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>


   <p>Archibald Cary (17211787), a great planter and a manufacturer, was at this time one of the two representatives of Chesterfield County in the House of Burgesses.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For GWs rather lukewarm recommendation of David Bell who had just lost his company in the Virginia Regiment, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0115" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 10 June 1757</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Drury Pucket was one of the draftees from Chesterfield County discharged in December 1756 (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0016" class="document">GWs Memorandum, 4 Dec. 1756</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0176-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Mrs. Cary was Mary Randolph Cary (17271781), daughter of Richard and Jane Bolling Randolph. She married Archibald Cary when she was about seventeen. Miss Randolph was probably Mrs. Carys unmarried sister Elizabeth.</p>

</div>
</div>
